description:
Mike Crouse discovered this plant right next to the Villager Peak Trail, which I had either not-noticed, or mistaken as a Ferocactus, on two previous trips!  This plant had bloomed earlier this year.

It was a perfect Echinocactus:

 - it has woolly fruit, near the tip of the barrel, and not the glabrous fruit, in a ring somewhat below the tip, of Ferocactus;

 - the number of ribs are 16, 18, and 19, not the 21 to 29 for Ferocactus;

 - the areoles have all stout spines, with the bristle-like non-rubst lower spines for Ferocactus.

As far as I know, this is the westernmost location for this species in the Borrego Valley area.
Alas, eight years later at least two of the ~7 barrels were dead:

https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/105133955

And three years after that, 11 years after this first observation, it was complete dead or close to it.  See:

https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/105074528

description:
Small Calidris observed with Sanderlings, Dunlin, Western Sandpiper and Least Sandpiper at Abbot's Lagoon a few days before the Point Reyes CBC.   Dark legs and feet, size smaller than Western Sandpiper, with a shorter bill, and in some photos the lack of any webbing between the toes can be seen. 
 The bird was fairly drab gray, and some uneven molt can be seen.  Cleanly eliminating Red-Necked Stint is difficult from these photos but Keith Hansen and Steve Howell had some better photos of the same individual taken the following day which helped.  Accepted by CBRC as Little Stint (2011-114).

Spores average 11.2 × 7.6 microns

description:
Widest coast redwood in Nisene Marks (at the widest point, 20 feet) and one of the few remaining virgin trees in Nisene Marks. A full scale measure operation of the tree has been underway and a complete map of the base is finished...
Base of tree: hollow and burned
Reiterations: two largest are around five feet in diameter at ten meters up
Height of tallest reiteration: around 150 to 160 feet (viewed from 100 feet up in tree)
At 100 feet, multiple lichens grew.
Redwood grows in a setting of madrones, tan oak, and coast redwoods.
Video from 100 feet up: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_OZwWf81hG4
The rotten branch leaning against the tree cannot be removed due to the redwood growing around the branch.

I'd come to visit a dear friend, whose heart stopped as he was being checked out in a hospital's catherization lab...   amazingly, he was shocked, stented, and sent home in 2 days.

Outside his living room I identified this bird:  of course with perfect equanimity, it's presence being only the merest coincidence.

We are quite sure that he killed a deer in the vineyard adjacent to our property. Also one of our dogs disappeared some months ago. Might it have been this puma???

Sorry about the poor photo. I was tidepooling and stepped on a large rock and this crab came scurrying out from under it. It isn't a type of crab I've seen before I don't think. Not a striped shore crab or porcelain crab. I suppose it could be a kelp crab but I don't think so. I would say the size was about 3 inches or so. It is facing towards the upper left side of the photo. You can see the right front pincher and the top of it is rough/ridged.
Here I'm identifying the ribbed limpet on the right bottom of the photo and the tiny dark one in the middle.

The one I'm identifying here is the tiny one next to the chiton on the left. After looking here: http://www.nmr-pics.nl/Fissurellidae/album/index.html I think it might be Diodora patagonica or Fissurella oriens although I don't know the distribution of those two. Just using the images. When I looked up those two on another site (like this one: http://www.gastropods.com/5/Shell_4435.shtml) the colors are different and I'm not so sure. These are hard to identify!
Do you think this is Mopalia lignosa?
This is what I think is called a tortoise shell limpet.

This one is really bothering me. It seems to be a California juniper which is also about all it could be. But I didn't think junipers had cones like this (in addition to the famous blue berries). These cones are identical to those pictured here:
http://mojavedesert.net/plants/shrubs/juniper.html

But I can't find a description of such cones in any floras. All say the "seed cones" are fleshy blue berries and the "pollen cones" are tiny.

I need to look into this more...
I'm almost positive these were the type. They had orange beaks (or underneath their beaks). What I was taken by was how much like ducks or geese they looked like when they were flying.

I finally saw what I'm pretty sure was a black sea hare! You can see how large it is by the photo with my foot (women's size 9) and I read: "the body of this species is relatively firm, and the parapodia are joined behind the siphon" and I think that's what's happening here.
With winter plumage.
What do you think? I didn't get a look at it flying, but it had a piercing kind of call. Anything else it could have been?

description:
So I'm out birding Mines Rd. with Scott, searching for Lewis's Woodpecker, when I stop to get a look at a bird.  When I'm convinced said bird is not our quarry, I notice a county cop car behind me, flashing its lights, no siren.  I pull over, and two officers get out, flank us, and procede to ask, in a friendly fashion, what we're doing driving so slowly out in the middle of nowhere.  They also point out that two young men in a car of Asian make looks suspicious in this part of the country, where apparently pairs of young men in Asian cars often prospect for promising places to grow weed.  We patiently explain that while we find plants of all kinds quite intriguing, we are not at this moment surveying for spots to grow that particular plant, and are, in fact, searching for a pink and green woodpecker.  Bemused, and perhaps even a little concerned, the officers advise us on the best places to spot elk (warning us not to shoot any), and even recommend a novel describing the kind of crime that occurs in this part of the country (the title of which I have sadly forgotten).

We live in an amazing country.
